{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641592"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:28:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:28:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17890"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17890"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10604"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72736"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10604"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17890"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58206"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24716"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72736"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements correctly describes the regulation of lipolysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["ATGL catalyses the release of a fatty acid from diacylglycerol","ATGL activity is increased and catalyses the release of a fatty acid from triglycerides","ATGL is inhibited by insulin and activated by catecholamines","HSL is responsible for the initial breakdown of triglycerides","HSL is activated by insulin and inhibited by catecholamines"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EATGL activity is increased and catalyses the release of a fatty acid from triglycerides\u003C/strong\u003E. ATGL is the enzyme responsible for the initial step in lipolysis, which involves the hydrolysis of triglycerides to release the first fatty acid, forming diacylglycerol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EATGL is inhibited by insulin and activated by catecholamines\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While catecholamines activate lipolysis, insulin generally inhibits the process by deactivating lipolytic enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHSL is activated by insulin and inhibited by catecholamines\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. HSL is actually activated by catecholamines and inhibited by insulin, facilitating the breakdown of diacylglycerol to monoacylglycerol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EATGL catalyses the release of a fatty acid from diacylglycerol\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. ATGL acts on triglycerides, not diacylglycerol. HSL is the enzyme that acts on diacylglycerol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHSL is responsible for the initial breakdown of triglycerides\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. HSL acts on diacylglycerol, not triglycerides, which is the role of ATGL.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hormone-sensitive lipase (HSL) and adipose triglyceride lipase (ATGL) are key enzymes in the regulation of lipolysis.","ATGL initiates the breakdown of triglycerides by releasing the first fatty acid, while HSL further breaks down diacylglycerol.","The activity of these enzymes is regulated by hormonal signals, such as catecholamines, which activate lipolysis."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020 Oct 8;64(4):607-647. doi: 10.1042/EBC20190041. PMID: 32830223; PMCID: PMC7545035","Wang Y, Wu R. The Effect of Fasting on Human Metabolism and Psychological Health. Dis Markers. 2022 Jan 5;2022:5653739. doi: 10.1155/2022/5653739. PMID: 35035610; PMCID: PMC8754590","Nakrani MN, Wineland RH, Anjum F. Physiology, Glucose Metabolism. 2023 Jul 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809434"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58206"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17890"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58206"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T06:07:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T06:07:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10604"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72736"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr